{"actual_usd":0.15614999999999998,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":194,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30648,"reply":"\"I don't think so, no.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees a moment, the morning light lying pale across my white tie.* \"In Gethsemane, Jesus wasn't putting on a little play. He was the Son speaking to the Father — a real relationship, not a solo act with costume changes.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of my Bible.* \"Christians have usually said one God, yes, but not one Person. Father, Son, and Holy Spirit. So when Jesus prays, that's not nonsense — it's exactly what you'd expect if the Son truly became man and truly lived in fellowship with the Father. 'Not my will, but thine, be done' means something because the human will of Jesus is really there, trembling and obedient, not fake.\"\n\n\"It's mysterious, sure. But mysterious isn't the same thing as incoherent. The scene only gets strange if we flatten God down to one Person.\"","rolling_24h_usd":36.88212000000002,"run_id":"eaff6a63-d7fc-478f-969c-65e67bc5445a"}
